Known issues - due to the randomness of how buildings are generated it is possible that a pokemart and center will
will try to be placed on the same section and if there is not enough space for both the center will be prioritized.
NPCs can get stuck on eachother if they are trying to move into eachother, this is because they are set to move until
they hit impassible terrain, and other NPCs are not considered impassable.
---------------------------
Assignment 1.01 - Pokemon board Generation.
---------------------------
Board has 3 front facing functions: 
genBoard(Board *b) - generates a board with random exit points (redacted)
genBoard(Board *b, int n, int s, int w, int e) - generates a board with set exit points. (redacted)
printBoard(Board *b) - prints the board for display
seedQueue is a queue used to hold the seeds of the terrain types used to grow terrain.
---------------------------
Assignment 1.02 - Pokemon World map Generation
---------------------------
Map has 7 functions:
5 movement functions: moveNorth(*m), moveEast(*m), moveSouth(*m), moveWest(*m) 
fly(*m, int x, int y) - moves to board[y][x]
initMap(*m) - sets position to 0,0 (200, 200) and generates the center board
printScreen(*m) - prints current position and the board
---------------------------
Assignment 1.03 - NPC movement costs 
---------------------------
MovementCosts has 3 functions to call:
initCost(MovementCosts *c, const Board *b) - sets the costs for each tile for all NPC types 
updateCosts(MovementCosts *c, const Board *b, int row, int col) - updates the min costs for each 
tile to reach a certain location (per NPC type)
printCosts(MovementCosts *c) - prints the costs of each tile for each NPC type 
Uses Dijkstras to calculate the min cost per tile. Dijkstras uses a generic heap that holds costNodes 
to find min.
---------------------------
Assignment 1.04 - NPC movement
---------------------------
NPCs have 6 different logic types for movement:
1. wanderer - moves in a straight line until it hits the edge of the terrain then it picks a new direction
2. hiker - moves towards the player using the hiker movement costs
3. rival - moves towards the player using the rival movement costs
4. pacer - moves back and forth in a straight line between until it hits impassable terrain then it turns around
5. sentry - does not move
6. explorer - moves in a straight line until it hits impassable terrain then it picks a new direction
Every NPC has a next move that is stored in the movement controller and is updated every time they move.
The movement controller has a performs each move then selects the next move for each NPC.
The movement controller is logically a heap, and characters are stored in a character map. 
---------------------------